
The Integer class in Java is a wrapper class that encapsulates a primitive int data
type into an object. This allows int values to be used in contexts where objects are 
required, such as with certain collections and APIs.
The Integer class also provides utility methods for operations involving integers.

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Converting a string to an integer
        String str = "12345";
        int num = Integer.parseInt(str);

        System.out.println("Parsed Integer: " + num); // Outputs: Parsed Integer: 12345

        // Comparing two integers
        int a = 10;
        int b = 20;

        int comparison = Integer.compare(a, b);
        System.out.println("Comparison Result: " + comparison); // Outputs: Comparison Result: -1 (a < b)

        // Using Integer.bitCount() to count the number of one-bits in an integer
        int bitValue = 7; // binary: 111
        int bitCount = Integer.bitCount(bitValue);

        System.out.println("Number of One-bits: " + bitCount); // Outputs: Number of One-bits: 3

        // Using Integer.reverse() to reverse the bit pattern of an integer
        int reversedBits = Integer.reverse(bitValue);
        System.out.println("Reversed Bits: " + reversedBits); // Outputs: Reversed Bits: -1073741824 (binary: 111...000)

